defaultSummarydefault&#xa0;
default1. The latest version of the HS2 Economic Case published at the end of October 2013 still contains faults 
defaultsome of 
defaultwhich have been pointed out in earlier versions. 
defaultSome other shortcomings are detailed too.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default2. My recommendation is to cancel HS2 now. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultOverstated Benefitsdefault&#xa0;
default3. 
defaultThe economic case still uses
default the basis that people do not work on trains and therefore any journey time saving results in added work (productivity). While
default the value of time has been changed, the principle that a shorter journey time leads to more worker output has not changed. 
defaultIt is well known that many people work on trains whether using a laptop, iPad, smartphone or simply reading documents. To continue t
defaulto ignore what happens in the real world is absurd.
default&#xa0;
default4. 
defaultPreviously the Department for Transport had anticipated that about 30% of HS2 passengers would be on business. National Passenger Surveys have regularly reported a similar proportion of business travellers on intercity routes on the West Coast Mainline (WC
defaultML), Midland Mainline (MML) and East Coast Mainline (ECML). 
defaulthttp://www.passengerfocus.org.uk/research/national-passenger-survey-introduction
default    See Stakeholde
defaultr Report
default5. 
defaultThe latest HS2 economic case now anticipates a much higher proportion of business travellers than previously, e.g. 66% for London Manchester. Such a high proportion of business travellers 
defaultis no longer in line with National Passenger Surveys.
default&#xa0;
default6. 
defaultThe HS2 economic case for HS2 is still calculated on the basis that passenger 
defaultticket prices will carry no premium over those for classic rail journeys. This lack of premium ticket pricing in the DfT’s HS2 passenger demand modelling was strongly challeng
defaulted by the Public Accounts Committee in 2012. 
defaulthttp://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmpubacc/464/12041801.htm
default   See questions 42 to 50
default and their answers.
